## Best Practices

### 1. Error Handling
- Always handle errors properly in middleware
- Use appropriate HTTP status codes
- Log errors for debugging
- Don't expose sensitive information in error responses

### 2. Performance
- Keep middleware lightweight and efficient
- Use caching where appropriate
- Avoid blocking operations in middleware
- Consider async operations for heavy tasks

### 3. Security
- Validate all inputs in middleware
- Sanitize data before processing
- Use secure defaults
- Implement proper authentication and authorization

### 4. Logging
- Log important events in middleware
- Include relevant context (user ID, IP, etc.)
- Use structured logging
- Don't log sensitive information

### 5. Configuration
- Make middleware configurable
- Use environment variables for sensitive config
- Provide sensible defaults
- Validate configuration on startup

## Middleware Order

### Global Middleware (Applied to all routes)
1. Recovery (panic handling)
2. Logging (request logging)
3. CORS (cross-origin requests)

### Route-Specific Middleware (Applied to specific groups)
1. Rate Limiting
2. Authentication
3. Authorization
4. Validation
5. Custom business logic

